---
import '../styles/global.css';

const TOOLS = 'https://tools.borck.education/';
const GH = 'https://github.com/michael-borck';

const work = [
  {
    kicker: 'Teaching & curriculum',
    title: 'Rebuilding what I teach, in the open',
    body: 'Six units retooled and two postgraduate degrees plus three executive courses built to use AI transparently and ethically, from first-year programming to executive strategy.',
    honest: "The hard part isn't the tech; it's operationalising “transparent and ethical” in a live unit. Some of it I got wrong first.",
    blurb: "I didn't add AI as a topic. I rebuilt the teaching around it, openly, with one rule: if students can use AI they should be told how, and I should be honest about my own use too. Six units retooled, two postgraduate units and three executive courses built from scratch. Teaching the same shift to a first-year programmer and a room of executives forces a useful clarity about what's universal and what changes by level. It runs the other way too: in introductory programming, students learn to code by building AI itself, writing a chatbot and then giving it a personality, using a small package I wrote (HandsOnAI).",
    links: [{ label: 'borck.education', href: 'https://borck.education' }],
  },
  {
    kicker: 'Local-AI research',
    title: 'Frontier-style AI on a budget, built at Curtin',
    body: 'An applied AI research lab running on secondhand hardware, so we can do real local-AI research without student data ever leaving the building.',
    honest: 'Secondhand GPUs come with a tax: driver traps, mismatched machines, a power supply sized one notch too small.',
    blurb: "It started with a constraint (no frontier cloud AI with student data) and became a research programme. An applied lab on secondhand hardware: training specialised models, benchmarking which model fits which GPU, and a free local-AI stack on the campus network. Frontier-style work on a shoestring, with a published methodology and deployed services behind it.",
    links: [{ label: 'locolabo.org', href: 'https://locolabo.org' }],
  },
  {
    kicker: 'Tools for students',
    title: 'AI you can actually recommend to students',
    body: 'Small desktop apps that each do one job (spoken-conversation practice, a tutor that won’t just give the answer, private career exploration), running on the student’s own laptop.',
    honest: 'A desktop app is a little more setup than a website. The trade is genuine data sovereignty.',
    blurb: "Small desktop apps that each own one job and run on the student's own laptop. Talk Buddy: rehearse a hard conversation before you have it. Study Buddy: a tutor that makes you argue for the answer instead of handing it over. Career Compass: career exploration where the résumé never leaves the machine. All free, all private.",
    links: [
      { label: 'talk-buddy', href: TOOLS + 'talk-buddy/' },
      { label: 'study-buddy', href: TOOLS + 'study-buddy/' },
      { label: 'career-compass', href: TOOLS + 'career-compass/' },
      { label: 'all tools', href: TOOLS },
    ],
  },
  {
    kicker: 'Tools for teaching staff',
    title: 'An AI assistant for the whole teaching lifecycle',
    body: 'Design a unit, audit it for accessibility, give rubric-aligned feedback, and close the loop on student surveys, privately, on your own machine.',
    honest: 'Each tool owns one job on purpose. No all-in-one platform to wrangle, no procurement battle.',
    blurb: "Four tools across the teaching lifecycle, each owning one job: Curriculum Curator (design a unit), UDL Lens (audit it for accessibility), FeedForward (rubric-aligned feedback the academic releases; the AI never edits student work), and InsightLens (turn eVALUate and Insight surveys into a decision for next term). The shared posture: AI assists at the boundary; the academic keeps the judgment.",
    links: [
      { label: 'insight-lens', href: TOOLS + 'insight-lens/' },
      { label: 'all teaching tools', href: TOOLS },
    ],
  },
  {
    kicker: 'Assessment at scale',
    title: 'Signals, not scores',
    body: 'AI reads what students submit (essays, code, presentations, even drafting history) and maps it to your rubric. You keep every judgment. It scales to large cohorts.',
    honest: 'The AI never grades. It points; the human decides. That boundary is the whole design.',
    blurb: "AI reads whatever a student submits (an essay, code, a recorded presentation, even a document's drafting trajectory) and maps what it finds to your rubric as observations, not grades. You read the signals, weigh them, assign the mark, and write the feedback. It makes a cohort of 300 readable without the AI ever marking, and assessing the evidence and the process is more defensible in an AI world than marking a final text.",
    links: [{ label: 'github.com/michael-borck', href: GH }],
  },
  {
    kicker: 'Governance',
    title: 'AI in teaching without sending data anywhere',
    body: 'The case (and the tools) for small, privacy-first AI that runs locally. As subscription and token costs climb, local-first is increasingly the sensible default.',
    honest: 'Local models are genuinely worse at frontier tasks. For conversation and governance, they’re more than enough.',
    blurb: "Most institutional AI adoption stalls on one question: where does the data go? The answer here is 'your own machine.' The case (and the working tools) for small, single-purpose, privacy-first AI that runs locally, with no telemetry and no shared cloud database. As subscription and token costs climb, local-first is increasingly the sensible default for education.",
    links: [{ label: 'locolabo.org', href: 'https://locolabo.org' }],
  },
  {
    kicker: 'The role',
    title: 'A year as a school’s first AI facilitator',
    body: 'Honest reflections on what it actually takes to help colleagues use AI well: what worked, what flopped, and what the role needs to look like at scale.',
    honest: 'A single embedded person doesn’t scale, and some of what worked, worked because it was one trusted person in the corridor.',
    blurb: "A candid account of a year as a school's first embedded AI Facilitator: how staff actually used the time (mostly not what you'd predict), what the Skills Passport changed, where workshops landed and where they flopped, and the honest finding: a single embedded person doesn't scale, and some of what worked, worked because it was one trusted person in the corridor.",
    links: [{ label: 'borck.education', href: 'https://borck.education' }],
  },
  {
    kicker: 'Building method',
    title: 'What AI lets one academic build, and where it breaks',
    body: 'Roughly thirty tools shipped solo, in conversation with AI. A working method, and an honest account of the failure modes.',
    honest: "“I shipped thirty things” becomes “I maintain thirty unmaintained things” without discipline.",
    blurb: "About thirty tools shipped solo, in conversation with AI, and an honest account of the failure modes: confidently-wrong code, the pull to delegate instead of think, the maintenance trap. The breadth is evidence, not the point; the working method and the disciplines that keep it sustainable are. The raw portfolio lives on GitHub; the polished subset is on the tools site. One example of the range: a small media pipeline that turns a markdown deck into a narrated video with sourced images, an avatar walk-on, and a chatbot grounded in the unit's documents, no recording studio required.",
    links: [
      { label: 'github.com/michael-borck', href: GH },
      { label: 'tools.borck.education', href: TOOLS },
    ],
  },
  {
    kicker: 'Authoring',
    title: 'Books written the way I tell students to',
    body: 'Framework books and a verb-by-verb Python series: published, open-licensed, and usable in your own units.',
    honest: 'AI made it possible; the places it would’ve quietly degraded the book are exactly the places that make a book worth reading.',
    blurb: "Two framework books and a verb-by-verb Python series: published, open-licensed, and usable in your own units. An honest look at writing them with AI: what it was genuinely good at, where the human had to hold the line on voice and the examples that matter, and the publishing reality nobody mentions.",
    links: [{ label: 'books.borck.education', href: 'https://books.borck.education' }],
  },
  {
    kicker: 'Simulations',
    title: 'Rehearse the situation before the situation',
    body: 'A platform that generates realistic workplace simulations (a company, AI “employees”, real tasks) so students can rehearse before a placement or capstone, at scale.',
    honest: "A simulation isn’t the real thing. But practice is practice, and rehearsed students show up ready.",
    blurb: "We send students into a placement, client project, or capstone having never rehearsed it, and that's hard to arrange and doesn't scale. So build the rehearsal. A platform that generates realistic workplace simulations (a company, AI 'employees', internal documents, real tasks) so a whole cohort can practise the role and the workflow before the real thing. A simulation isn't the real thing, but practice is practice, and rehearsed students show up ready. One such world, CloudCore (a firm recovering from a data breach), is taught across five units, with AI staff who only answer during business hours and a story that time-releases as the term unfolds.",
    links: [
      { label: 'locoensayo.org', href: 'https://locoensayo.org' },
      { label: 'simulations.borck.education', href: 'https://simulations.borck.education/' },
    ],
  },
];

const collab = [
  { name: 'Keep Asking', desc: 'What ~15,000 student-AI conversations taught us, with colleagues across Marketing, Supply Chain, and People & Culture.' },
  { name: 'UDL Lens', desc: 'Accessibility auditing of assessments, with Luke Butcher: AI drafts, the academic decides.' },
  { name: 'The AI Skills Passport', desc: 'Self-paced AI literacy, adopted and told from a staff user’s point of view.' },
  { name: 'WorkReady', desc: 'An internship-rehearsal simulation, led by its project lead in the School of Marketing & Management.' },
  { name: 'Career Compass', desc: 'Privacy-first career exploration, fronted by the careers / People & Culture team.' },
  { name: 'Document Lens', desc: 'Transparent, reproducible AI (not a chatbot) for reading sustainability reports at scale, with research colleagues across schools.' },
  { name: 'AI digital humans', desc: 'Lifelike avatars students rehearse high-stakes speaking with, with real-time feedback. An Assessment 2030 pilot, with a Management & Marketing colleague.' },
  { name: 'Can AI grade?', desc: 'An ethics-approved study that put GenAI marking to the test, with a Science & Engineering colleague. The honest finding: good at the average, bad at the precise.' },
];

const exploring = [
  'Small local models as genuine thinking partners: engineered for variance, not just precision.',
  'A capstone where students ship real, specialised AI and leave with it on their résumé.',
  'Multimodal assessment signals: reading the process a student followed, not just the final artefact.',
  'Local-first as the default for education as subscription and token costs climb.',
];

// JSON-LD Person entity. Shared @id with borck.dev consolidates the scattered
// estate into one entity for search + AI answer engines. borck.consulting is
// intentionally omitted (kept separate).
const personSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Person',
  '@id': 'https://borck.dev/#michael-borck',
  name: 'Michael Borck',
  givenName: 'Michael',
  familyName: 'Borck',
  url: 'https://bigpicture.borck.dev',
  jobTitle: 'Lecturer & AI Facilitator',
  worksFor: {
    '@type': 'CollegeOrUniversity',
    name: 'Curtin University',
    department: 'School of Marketing and Management, Faculty of Business and Law',
  },
  knowsAbout: [
    'AI in education', 'privacy-first AI', 'local language models',
    'assessment design', 'educational technology', 'work-integrated learning',
  ],
  sameAs: [
    'https://borck.dev',
    'https://borck.education',
    'https://tools.borck.education',
    'https://books.borck.education',
    'https://research.borck.dev',
    'https://resume.borck.dev',
    'https://locolabo.org',
    'https://locoensayo.org',
    'https://conversationnotdelegation.com',
    'https://github.com/michael-borck',
    'https://www.linkedin.com/in/michaelborck',
    'https://orcid.org/0000-0002-0950-6396',
  ],
};
---
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8" />
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
  <title>Michael Borck: the big picture</title>
  <meta name="description" content="A map of the AI teaching, tools, and research Michael Borck has built at Curtin: what it's for, who it helps, and what he learned (including what didn't work)." />
  <link rel="icon" href="/favicon.svg" />
  <link rel="canonical" href="https://bigpicture.borck.dev/" />

  <!-- Open Graph / LinkedIn / Facebook -->
  <meta property="og:type" content="website" />
  <meta property="og:site_name" content="bigpicture.borck.dev" />
  <meta property="og:url" content="https://bigpicture.borck.dev/" />
  <meta property="og:title" content="Michael Borck: the big picture" />
  <meta property="og:description" content="The AI teaching, tools, and research I've built at Curtin: what it's for, who it helps, and what I learned. Conversation, not Delegation." />
  <meta property="og:image" content="https://bigpicture.borck.dev/og.png" />
  <meta property="og:image:width" content="1200" />
  <meta property="og:image:height" content="630" />
  <meta property="og:image:alt" content="Conversation, not Delegation: the AI teaching, tools and research of Michael Borck, Curtin University." />

  <!-- Twitter / X -->
  <meta name="twitter:card" content="summary_large_image" />
  <meta name="twitter:title" content="Michael Borck: the big picture" />
  <meta name="twitter:description" content="The AI teaching, tools, and research I've built at Curtin. Conversation, not Delegation." />
  <meta name="twitter:image" content="https://bigpicture.borck.dev/og.png" />

  <!-- Person entity for search + AI answer engines -->
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(personSchema)} />
</head>
<body>

<div class="corner"><a href="https://borck.dev">&larr; borck<span class="tld">.dev</span></a></div>

<header class="hero">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="eyebrow">Michael Borck &middot; Lecturer &amp; AI Facilitator &middot; Curtin University</div>
    <h1>Conversation, <span class="accent">not Delegation</span></h1>
    <div class="h1sub">a way of working with AI, and the teaching, tools, and research built on it</div>
    <p class="lede">AI should amplify human thinking, not replace it. This is a map of what I&rsquo;ve built and taught at Curtin to put that into practice: small, honest, privacy-first, and useful to the people who&rsquo;ll actually use it.</p>
    <div class="cta">
      <a class="btn primary" href="#work">See the work &darr;</a>
      <a class="btn ghost" href="https://conversationnotdelegation.com">The idea behind it</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</header>

<div class="about">
  <div class="wrap">
    This is a map, not a brochure. Each entry leads with <strong>what it&rsquo;s for and who it helps</strong>, says honestly <strong>what didn&rsquo;t work</strong>. Click any card for more, then jump to the real thing.
  </div>
</div>

<section id="work">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="sechead"><h2>The work</h2><span class="count">// ten threads, one idea</span></div>
    <div class="grid">
      {work.map((w, i) => (
        <button type="button" class="card" data-dialog={`d${i}`} aria-haspopup="dialog">
          <div class="kicker">{w.kicker}</div>
          <h3>{w.title}</h3>
          <p>{w.body}</p>
          <div class="honest">{w.honest}</div>
          <div class="go">Read more &rarr;</div>
        </button>
      ))}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

{work.map((w, i) => (
  <dialog class="sheet" id={`d${i}`}>
    <div class="sheet-inner">
      <button type="button" class="sheet-close" data-close aria-label="Close">&times;</button>
      <div class="kicker">{w.kicker}</div>
      <h3>{w.title}</h3>
      <p class="blurb">{w.blurb}</p>
      <div class="sheet-links">
        {w.links.map((l) => (<a href={l.href}>{l.label} &rarr;</a>))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </dialog>
))}

<section class="collab">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="sechead"><h2>Built with colleagues &middot; used across Curtin</h2></div>
    <p class="secintro">The best of this work isn&rsquo;t mine alone: it&rsquo;s co-taught, adopted, and fronted by the people who use it. That&rsquo;s the point.</p>
    <ul class="collablist">
      {collab.map((c) => (
        <li><b>{c.name}</b><span>{c.desc}</span></li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="explore">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="sechead"><h2>What I&rsquo;m exploring now</h2></div>
    <ul>
      {exploring.map((e) => (<li>{e}</li>))}
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<footer>
  <div class="wrap">
    <strong>Michael Borck</strong> &middot; Lecturer &amp; AI Facilitator &middot; School of Marketing and Management (SoMM), Faculty of Business and Law, Curtin University
    <div class="flinks">
      <a href="https://borck.dev">borck.dev</a>
      <a href="https://borck.education">borck.education</a>
      <a href="https://tools.borck.education">tools.borck.education</a>
      <a href="https://books.borck.education">books.borck.education</a>
      <a href="https://research.borck.dev">research.borck.dev</a>
      <a href="https://locolabo.org">locolabo.org</a>
      <a href="https://github.com/michael-borck">github</a>
      <a href="mailto:michael.borck@curtin.edu.au">email</a>
    </div>
    <p class="fine">The map, not the territory: every link goes to the real thing. Built in conversation with AI, of course.</p>
  </div>
</footer>

<script>
  // open a card's detail dialog
  document.querySelectorAll('[data-dialog]').forEach((btn) => {
    btn.addEventListener('click', () => {
      const d = document.getElementById(btn.getAttribute('data-dialog'));
      if (d && typeof d.showModal === 'function') d.showModal();
    });
  });
  // close: × button, or click on the backdrop (Esc is handled natively)
  document.querySelectorAll('dialog.sheet').forEach((d) => {
    d.addEventListener('click', (e) => { if (e.target === d) d.close(); });
    d.querySelectorAll('[data-close]').forEach((b) => b.addEventListener('click', () => d.close()));
  });
</script>

</body>
</html>
